1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O g6 $5 {A funny little move in
the Queen's Indian Defence. There's no way it's the best, but contrary to the main lines, white
generally starts scratching his head after this. As Bartek was also leading by
half a point, this line was perfectly suitable.} 6. d4 Bg7 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Nxe4
Bxe4 9. Bg5 f6 $5 10. Be3 Nc6 11. Qd2 (11. d5 {is the try to punish black, but
following} Ne7 12. dxe6 dxe6 13. Qa4+ Bc6 14. Qb3 O-O {black's position is
strange yet sound.}) 11... O-O 12. Rfd1 Ne7 13. Bh6 d5 (13... Bxh6 14. Qxh6 d5
{was similar in 1-0 (37) Jakovenko,D (2730)-Ipatov,A (2613) Saint-Quentin FRA
2014}) 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. cxd5 exd5 16. b4 a5 $5 17. b5 a4 $5 {Black's play
looks antipositional; he is saddled with a very backward c-pawn. However, let
us say I was hungry during the game, and the b-pawn smelled quite nice... and
besides, black's play is not unsound, just concrete.} 18. Ne1 Ra5 19. Bxe4 dxe4
20. Ng2 $6 (20. Rab1 {was the way to go, and honestly more natural.} Qd7 21.
Qc2 Nd5 22. Qc4 $11) 20... Rxb5 21. Qc2 Nd5 $1 22. Ne3 {White's position looks
shaky, but his disadvantage is actually small.} (22. Qxa4 {works miserably:}
Nc3 23. Qc4 Nxd1 24. Qxb5 Qxd4 $19) 22... Rf7 ({Of course, better is} 22...
Nxe3 23. fxe3 Ra5 24. Qxe4 Re8 25. Qd3 Qd5 $15 {but I harbored hopes of a
mating attack yet again...}) 23. Nxd5 Qxd5 24. Qxa4 Rb2 25. e3 Qf5 26. Rf1 Rb5
({The immediate} 26... h5 {expires my rook on b2 after} 27. Rab1 {.}) 27. Rac1
h5 28. Qc2 h4 29. Qe2 Ra5 (29... h3 $1 {would have given White back rank
difficulties in the long run.}) 30. Rc2 hxg3 (30... h3 {was still the move.})
31. fxg3 Qd5 32. Rfc1 c5 33. dxc5 bxc5 34. Qd2 Qxd2 35. Rxd2 Rfa7 36. Rcc2 {
This endgame should be drawn, but black can never lose. Counting in the mutual
time deficiency, Black has considerable chances to make something happen.} f5
37. Kf2 Kf6 38. Rd5 Ke6 39. Rdd2 (39. Rdxc5 Rxc5 40. Rxc5 Rxa2+ 41. Kg1 Re2 42.
Rc3 {didn't look particularly nice for White, with his king cut to the back
rank and rook tied down, but he should be holding.}) 39... R7a6 40. h4 Rd6 41.
Re2 $1 {The right decision, as a pure rook ending has White totally passive.}
Rd3 42. Rb2 Ra6 $6 {Safe and slow.} (42... c4 {was more efficient.} 43. Rb6+
Rd6) 43. Rec2 Kd6 44. a4 Ra3 (44... Rxa4 $5 45. Rb6+ Kd5 46. Rxg6 c4 47. Rg8 c3
48. Rc8 Rc4 $15) 45. Rb5 Rc6 46. a5 c4 47. h5 gxh5 48. Rxf5 Rc5 49. Rf6+ Kd5 {
White has defended excellently so far, but here it was necessary to check
carefully — both the variations and the moves themselves.} 50. Rf5+ $6 ({
The proper check was} 50. Rd2+ Rd3 51. Ra2 $1 $132) 50... Kc6 51. Rf4 (51. Rf6+
$3 {was now critical.} Kb5 52. Rb6+ Kxa5 53. Rb8 c3 54. Ke2 {By some miracle
black can make no progress.}) 51... Kb5 52. Rxe4 Kb4 $1 {The a-pawn is a
sitting hamburger, but black must get the soda before it runs out.} 53. Ke2 Kb3
54. Rc1 Raxa5 (54... Ra2+ {chasing the white king away was more accurate.}) 55.
Rb1+ Kc2 56. Rb4 c3 57. g4 h4 58. g5 Rxg5 59. Rxh4 Rg2+ $2 (59... Rab5 {
was winning, but it was still far from trivial:} 60. Rxb5 Rxb5 61. e4 Rc5 $1
62. Rh8 (62. Ke3 Kb3 63. Rh1 c2 64. Kf4 c1=Q+ 65. Rxc1 Rxc1 66. e5 Kc4 67. e6
Re1 68. Kf5 Kd5) 62... Kb2 63. Rb8+ Kc1 64. Rb7 c2 65. Rb4 Rc6 {and eventually
black should prevail — in another 42 moves, according to tablebases.}) 60. Kf3
Rd2 $2 (60... Rag5 61. Rh3 Rg8 $17) 61. Rhc4 $2 ({Apparently, it was time to
start pushing with} 61. e4 {After a long think, the computer claims it's a
draw; black's chief difficulty is his Kc2.}) 61... Rd3 {Now the black king
slips out and the win is not in doubt.} 62. Kf4 Kd2 63. Rb1 Rxe3 64. Rh1 Re2
65. Rd4+ Kc2 66. Rb4 Ra8 67. Kf3 Re7 68. Rh6 Rf8+ 69. Kg3 Rg7+ 70. Kh2 Kc1 71.
